{{no footnotes|date=November 2009}} {{Infobox motorsport venue | Name = Asheville-Weaverville Speedway | Image = | Location = Flat Creek Township, [[Buncombe County, North Carolina|Buncombe County]], near [[Weaverville, North Carolina|Weaverville]], [[North Carolina]] | Capacity = over 7,000 | Opened = 1951 | Closed = 1987 | Events = Grand National Series <small>(now [[Sprint Cup Series]])</small> | Layout1 = Dirt [[Oval track racing|oval track]] | Miles_first = True | Length_km = 0.87 | Length_mi = 0.54 | Banking = }}
The '''Asheville-Weaverville Speedway''' near [[Weaverville, North Carolina|Weaverville]], [[North Carolina]], [[United States|USA]] was considered to be site for the old-school [[NASCAR]] races in both the ''Grand National'' and the ''Winston Cup'' eras (which is now known as the ''[[Monster Energy Cup Series]]''). None of the active drivers that are in the Sprint Cup Series today have ever raced at Asheville-Weaverville Speedway. Even some of the legends like [[Darrell Waltrip]] and [[Kyle Petty]] have never raced on the track due to the timing of their careers. From [[1951 in NASCAR|1951]] to [[1969 in NASCAR|1969]], the race course offered some wins from drivers like [[Richard Petty]], Bob Flock, Fonty Flock, Lee Petty, and a win by Fireball Roberts. As a dirt [[oval track racing|oval track]], the speedway helped served its purpose during the dirt-dominated formative years of what is now called the ''NASCAR Sprint Cup Series''. The track was later paved over. Other NASCAR legends like [[Banjo Matthews]], [[Ralph Earnhardt]], [[Junior Johnson]], and [[Cotton Owens]] had made notable appearances here.
The track was closed from the 1970s to racing, until North Buncombe High School was built on the property of the former track. In the 1970s and 1980s the track was used as softball fields and sports practice fields. The track itself had been disabled by first placing earthen barriers on opposite sides of the track, and later, concrete barriers at 8 locations around the track.
An anti-noise ordinance was used to shut down the track after years of racing; this fight was staged as early as the [[1970 in NASCAR|1970 racing season]] when a group of citizens petitioned their city council to shut down the track. Originally, the objectors were [[hotel]] operators but 75% of people who read the [[Asheville Citizen-Times|Asheville Citizen]] wanted that track to be closed in a poll done in the summer of 1987. However, by that time, the track had already been physically disabled for racing purposes. [[Urbanization]] and progress forced the property to be closed, demolished, and re-zoned for educational purposes.
The property is now occupied by [[North Buncombe High School]] with 1117 students.
