{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Infobox venue | stadium_name = Glebe Park | nickname = "The Glebe" | image = [[File:Glebe Park, Brechin 180321.jpg|250px]] | caption = View of the David H Will Stand | pushpin_map = Scotland Angus | pushpin_mapsize = 250 | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Angus | pushpin_label_position = left | coordinates = {{coord|56|44|07|N|2|39|23|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Brechin]], [[Scotland]] | broke_ground = | opened = 1919 | awards = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Brechin City F.C.]] | operator = | surface = [[Lawn|Grass]] | construction_cost = | architect = | former_names = | tenants = [[Brechin City F.C.]] (1919–present) | seating_capacity ={{SPFL-stadiums|brechin}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/scotland//brechin_city.htm |title=Brechin City Football Club |publisher=Scottish Football Ground Guide |accessdate=11 November 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410095612/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/scotland//hibernian.htm |archivedate=10 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> (1,519 seated)<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18868680 Rangers' Ramsdens Cup tie will go ahead in Brechin] - BBC Sport, 17 July 2012</ref> }}
'''Glebe Park''' is a [[association football|football]] stadium in [[Brechin]], [[Scotland]], which is the home ground of [[Brechin City F.C.|Brechin City]].
Glebe Park opened in 1919.<ref name = "inglis 430">{{harvnb|Inglis|1996|p=430}}</ref> The ground had just one portable stand, which had been used at the [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] agricultural show.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> Brechin City joined the [[Scottish Football League]] in [[1929–30 in Scottish football|1929]], when a pavilion was added and the Cemetery End terrace was covered.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> The biggest ever attendance was 8,123, against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in a [[Scottish Cup]] tie played on 3 February 1973.<ref name="inglis 430"/> This attendance was greater than the population of Brechin.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> Floodlights were installed and used for the first time in 1977, in a match against [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]].<ref name = "inglis 430"/>
[[File:Glebe Park. - geograph.org.uk - 43596.jpg|thumbnail|left|Glebe Park in 1983]]
The old stand was replaced by a new Main Stand, with 290 seats, in 1981.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> Sponsorship by the [[Stewart Milne]] group and a [[Football Trust]] grant of £210,000 financed the construction of a 1,228 seat stand at the Trinity Road end of the ground.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> This stand had double the capacity of Brechin City's average attendance, which attracted criticism from non-league clubs in England, who believed that the Football Trust should fund their developments instead.<ref name = "inglis 430"/>
Unusually, the largest stand in the ground was built behind the goal, rather than the side opposite the Main Stand.<ref name = "inglis 430"/> This was because that side is constrained by a terrace and the Glebe Park hedge, which runs past more than half of the pitch.<ref name = "inglis 430"/><ref name = "hedge row">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/brechin_dig_heels_in_over_hedge_row_1_1031846|title=Brechin dig heels in over hedge row|work=sport.scotsman.com|publisher=Johnston Press|date=27 March 2009|accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref><ref name = "foul">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brechin_city/7828495.stm|title=Brechin pitch falls foul of Uefa|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=BBC |date=14 January 2009|accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref> The hedge was threatened in 2009 because Glebe Park's pitch dimensions were too small for it to meet [[UEFA]] requirements, at just 67 yards wide.<ref name = "inglis 430"/><ref name = "hedge row"/><ref name = "foul"/> A fine was suspended by the [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] because Brechin City carried out some work to resolve the problem.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/cowdenbeath_haven_t_made_enough_effort_insists_sfa_1_798310|title=Cowdenbeath haven't made enough effort, insists SFA|work=sport.scotsman.com|publisher=Johnston Press|date=31 March 2010|accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref> There is a small training pitch behind the hedge.
Glebe Park has also been used for the [[reserve team]] matches of [[Scottish Premier League]] club [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].
